#If paired-end sequencing data, the forward and reverse fastq files contain reads in matched order.

#path to your FASTQ folder files

#sort samples based on pattern into forward and reverse

fnFs <- sort(list.files(path, pattern="_R1_001.fastq.gz", full.names = TRUE))
fnRs <- sort(list.files(path, pattern="_R2_001.fastq.gz", full.names = TRUE))
#separate the samples names into 
sample.names <- sapply(strsplit(basename(fnFs), "_"), `[`, 1)
#plot the quality scores for PE sample 151 and 152 which is number 1 and 2 in the list
plotQualityProfile(fnFs[7:8])

#mean quality score at each position is shown by the green line
#get the filter
filtFs <- file.path(path, "filtered", paste0(sample.names, "_F_filt.fastq.gz"))
#make sure to read the the filter data
filtRs <- file.path(path, "filtered", paste0(sample.names, "_R_filt.fastq.gz"))
names(filtFs) <- sample.names
names(filtRs) <- sample.names
#here we will truncate from 0 to 350 with no NNNs and default quality below 20 for Phred score
# maxEE c(2,2) as default which means how many mistakes you would like to accept  #parameter sets the maximum number of “expected errors” allowed in a read
#take some time, bring a cup of coffee until it can be ready.
out <- filterAndTrim(fnFs, filtFs, fnRs, filtRs, truncLen=c(350,0),
                     maxN=0, maxEE=c(2,2), truncQ=2, rm.phix=TRUE,
                     compress=TRUE)

#here we will show the first few sequences including the abundance of every contigs (the output of merging )

#Clustering the contigs into ASV (or high resolution OTU)
seqtab <- makeSequenceTable(mergers)
#let's know how many ASVs exists on the our cohort. 
dim(seqtab) #the second number is what you are looking for.
## [1]    153 159819
#chimera in mixing two different sequences are mixed together,chimera in Greek mythology monster :D
seqtab.nochim <- removeBimeraDenovo(seqtab, method="consensus", multithread=TRUE, 
                                    minParentAbundance=15,
                                    minFoldParentOverAbundance=4,
                                    verbose=TRUE)
## Identified 78054 bimeras out of 159819 input sequences.
#see how much ASVs have been left after removing chimera sequences
dim(seqtab.nochim)
## [1]   153 81765
##print it as % #chimera make up including abundance 
#if you got less than 50 % of the original input, you have to use less strict measures up there.
sum(seqtab.nochim)/sum(seqtab)*100
## [1] 78.22183
#Luckily, we don't
getN <- function(x) sum(getUniques(x))
track <- cbind(out, sapply(dadaFs, getN), sapply(dadaRs, getN), sapply(mergers, getN), rowSums(seqtab.nochim))
# If processing a single sample, remove the sapply calls: e.g. replace sapply(dadaFs, getN) with getN(dadaFs)
colnames(track) <- c("input", "filtered", "denoisedF", "denoisedR", "merged", "nonchim")
rownames(track) <- sample.names
#this will write a data frame 
write.csv(as.data.frame(track),"track.csv")
#######################################################
write.table(t(seqtab.nochim), "seqtab.txt", sep="\t", row.names=TRUE, col.names=NA, quote=FALSE)
uniquesToFasta(seqtab.nochim, fout="rep-seqs.fna", ids=colnames(seqtab.nochim))
